(2. COLLABORATIVE DESIGN) show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(Cyberspace was designed in collaboration with Claude \(Anthropic\), an AI) show newline
(assistant. This collaboration is documented in Memo-056.) show newline
() show newline
(The interaction model: human provides vision and constraints, AI) show newline
(provides implementation and exploration. Neither could have built this) show newline
(alone.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
(3. NAMING COHERENCE) show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(Knuth's principle from TAOCP: names should be consistent across the) show newline
(totality of a system. When we renamed 'RFC' to 'Memo' internally, we) show newline
(applied s/rfc/memo/g globally - not just to files being edited, but to) show newline
(every reference in the codebase.) show newline
() show newline
(Single source of truth extends to terminology. MEMO_NUMBER_WIDTH is) show newline
(defined once; the four-digit format flows from that constant through) show newline
(Scheme and shell. When the namespace overflows to five digits, one) show newline
(change propagates everywhere.) show newline
() show newline
(Piecemeal renaming creates inconsistent states where variables say one) show newline
(thing and filenames say another. The systematic approach is the only) show newline
(approach.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
(4. TARGET ENVIRONMENTS) show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(Primary targets:) show newline
() show newline
(  * macOS \(Apple Silicon\) - Cyberspace.app native shell) show newline
(  * Linux - including MIT Athena) show newline
(  * Any POSIX system with CHICKEN Scheme 5.x) show newline
() show newline
(The system should feel native on a Mac, work cleanly on Athena, and) show newline
(build anywhere Scheme runs.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
(5. THE SCHEME BENEATH) show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(Scheme is the implementation language, not the user interface. The) show newline
(novice sees a shell; the schemer sees a REPL. Same system, different) show newline
(lenses.) show newline
() show newline
(By default, Scheme internals are hidden:) show newline
() show newline
(  * Inspector disabled - errors show simple messages, not debug> prompts) show newline
(  * Exception display uses plain language, not 'unbound variable') show newline
(  * Help shows commands, not S-expressions) show newline
(  * The : prompt is a portal, not a lambda) show newline
() show newline
(Schemers opt in with \(enable-inspector!\) and see the machinery. The) show newline
(abstraction layer is permeable but not transparent.) show newline
() show newline
(This is not dumbing down. It is layered revelation - the same principle) show newline
(that makes Cyberspace.app feel native on Mac while running pure Scheme) show newline
(underneath.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
(6. THE SCRUTINIZER) show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(Consistency requires tooling. The scrutinizer audits tone and) show newline
(terminology across library and code.) show newline
() show newline
(Two failure modes:) show newline
() show newline
(  * Overreach - poetry where precision needed, whimsy in error messages) show newline
(  * Underreach - dry jargon where warmth appropriate, internal vocabulary leaking through) show newline
() show newline
(Passes:) show newline
() show newline
(  * Vocabulary audit - banned terms in user-facing strings) show newline
(  * Tone consistency - memos vs help vs errors) show newline
(  * S-expression exposure - Scheme leaking to surface) show newline
() show newline
(Interface:) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(    \(scrutinize\)               ; both passes \(default\)) show newline
(    \(scrutinize 'library\)      ; memos only) show newline
(    \(scrutinize 'code\)         ; code only) show newline
(    \(scrutinize #f\)            ; disable) show newline
(    *scrutinize-realmtime*     ; parameter, default #f) show newline
(    \(scrutinize-realmtime! #t\) ; enable during dev) show newline
() show newline
(Realmtime mode invokes spacetime - scrutiny flows through the realm as) show newline
(time passes. When enabled, violations surface as modules load. Off in) show newline
(production, on in beta.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
(7. FORGE AND SMELTER) show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(The forge module generates pronounceable passwords using Markov chains) show newline
(on digraph statistics. The lineage traces back to Multics.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(7.1 Heritage) show newline
(------------) show newline
() show newline
(Original design by Morrie Gasser in PL/1 on Multics. Gasser, author of) show newline
('Building a Secure Computer System' \(1988\), carried the code forward to) show newline
(VAX/VMS where it remained in PL/1 until the Alpha transition.) show newline
() show newline
(When DEC moved to Alpha architecture, PL/1 wasn't in the initial) show newline
(compiler release. The code had to be expunged from the TCB. Derrell) show newline
(Piper and Jon Callas rewrote it for VMS 6.0 \(circa 1991\): Piper wrote) show newline
(the BLISS system service for the Trusted Computing Base; Callas wrote) show newline
(the user-mode TPU smelter.) show newline
() show newline
(US and EU DEC patents were filed on the design \(now expired\). The) show newline
(terminology - forge, smelter - comes from metallurgy: the smelter) show newline
(refines raw ore \(word lists\) into workable material \(digraph) show newline
(statistics\); the forge shapes the final product \(pronounceable words\).) show newline
() show newline
(Callas later became a principal author of OpenPGP \(RFC 4880\) and) show newline
(co-founded PGP Corporation and Silent Circle. He remains a planned beta) show newline
(tester for Cyberspace.) show newline
() show newline
(The chain of custody: Gasser \(Multics PL/1\) > Piper/Callas \(VMS 6.0) show newline
(BLISS/TPU\) > Cyberspace \(Scheme\).) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(7.2 Design) show newline
(----------) show newline
() show newline
(The smelter reads word lists and extracts digraph \(character pair\)) show newline
(statistics:) show newline
() show newline
(  * Starting pair frequency - which pairs begin words) show newline
(  * Transition probability - given 'ab', what characters follow) show newline
(  * Termination markers - which pairs end words) show newline
() show newline
(The forge walks these statistics with weighted random selection,) show newline
(producing words that follow the phonetic patterns of the source) show newline
(language. Entropy is tracked in 'decibits' \(tenths of bits\) to quantify) show newline
(password strength.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(7.3 Languages) show newline
(-------------) show newline
() show newline
(Original VMS languages: English, Latin, Italian, Dutch, Sindarin,) show newline
(Webster. The VT100 diacriticals were encoded in DEC MCS \(Multinational) show newline
(Character Set\).) show newline
() show newline
(Cyberspace expansion to 40+ languages follows roughly the operational) show newline
(map of the Office of Strategic Services - another egg for those who) show newline
(recognize the geography:) show newline
() show newline
(  * Western Europe: French, German, Spanish, Portuguese) show newline
(  * Iberia: Catalan, Galician, Basque) show newline
(  * Nordic \(resistance networks\): Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Finnish) show newline
(  * Atlantic fringe: Irish, Welsh, Scottish Gaelic, Breton) show newline
(  * Balkans \(partisan country\): Greek, Albanian, Serbian, Croatian, Slovenian, Macedonian) show newline
(  * Eastern front: Polish, Czech, Slovak, Hungarian, Romanian) show newline
(  * Baltic: Lithuanian, Latvian, Estonian) show newline
(  * Soviet theater: Russian, Ukrainian, Bulgarian) show newline
(  * Near East: Turkish, Armenian) show newline
(  * Mediterranean \(George Cross island\): Maltese) show newline
(  * Detachment 101: Vietnamese, Thai, Lao, Korean) show newline
(  * Literary: Sindarin \(Tolkien's Elvish\), Dante's Divina Commedia) show newline
() show newline
(Word lists sourced from Hunspell, LibreOffice, SCOWL, OpenTaal, Eldamo,) show newline
(and the Princeton Dante Project. All diacriticals converted to UTF-8.) show newline
() show newline
(Sindarin preserves Tolkien's circumflexes: Manwë, Aulë, Andúril.) show newline
(Dante's medieval Italian sits alongside. The OSS framing is itself an) show newline
(easter egg - layers of meaning for those who dig.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(7.4 Related Standards) show newline
(---------------------) show newline
() show newline
(Forge predates but relates to two password generation standards:) show newline
() show newline
(  * FIPS 181 \(1993\) - Automated Password Generator. Uses trigraph \(3-letter\) statistics and hyphenation rules. More structured but less natural. Forge's digraph approach \(1991\) produces smoother results by learning from actual language patterns rather than syllable rules.) show newline
(  * OPIE/S/Key - One-time Passwords In Everything. Uses a fixed 2048-word dictionary optimized for spoken communication over phone lines. Words are short and phonetically distinct. Different goal: memorability for one-time use vs. pronounceability for permanent passwords.) show newline
() show newline
(Forge's contribution was combining Markov chain language modeling with) show newline
(entropy tracking - knowing not just that a password sounds right, but) show newline
(exactly how many bits of randomness it contains.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(7.5 Interface) show newline
(-------------) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(    \(forge\)              ; one English word) show newline
(    \(forge 5\)            ; five English words) show newline
(    \(forge 'sindarin\)    ; one Elvish word) show newline
(    \(forge 'latin 3\)     ; three Latin words) show newline
(    \(forge 'passphrase\)  ; 4-word passphrase) show newline
(    \(forge 'german 'passphrase 6\) ; 6-word German passphrase) show newline
() show newline
(Each word reports its entropy. Passphrases join words with hyphens. The) show newline
(forge is an easter egg - undocumented in help, discovered by schemers) show newline
(exploring the REPL.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(7.6 Cryptographic Entropy) show newline
(-------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(Passwords fall naturally out of pronounceable words when the entropy) show newline
(source is sound. Forge uses /dev/urandom for cryptographically secure) show newline
(randomness, not pseudo-random generators.) show newline
() show newline
(Boot-time verification runs automatically on module load:) show newline
() show newline
(  * Confirms /dev/urandom exists and is readable) show newline
(  * Reads 256 test bytes and checks byte distribution) show newline
(  * Verifies no single byte appears more than ~10% \(bias detection\)) show newline
(  * Confirms at least 100 distinct byte values \(diversity check\)) show newline
() show newline
(If verification fails, the module refuses to load. An easter egg with) show newline
(real security - someone exploring the REPL discovers \(forge\) and gets) show newline
(actual cryptographic passwords, not toys.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
(8. THE NOVICE INTERFACE) show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(Cyberspace must be approachable by normal people. The terminal is for) show newline
(operators. A friendly interface layer serves everyone else.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(8.1 The Problem) show newline
(---------------) show newline
() show newline
(A novice asked: "Why would I want to use this? I have iCloud. They have) show newline
(recipes and cat pictures.") show newline
() show newline
(Valid question. The answer must be compelling without mentioning) show newline
(Ed25519, SPKI certificates, hash chains, Merkle trees, or S-expressions.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(8.2 What Novices Want) show newline
(---------------------) show newline
() show newline
(They don't want a distributed cryptographic vault. They want:) show newline
() show newline
(  * My stuff is mine - Not rented from a corporation) show newline
(  * It survives - No company shutdown deletes my photos) show newline
(  * I control sharing - Family, not platforms) show newline
(  * Privacy - My recipes aren't AI training data) show newline
(  * Legacy - Grandkids can inherit the vault) show newline
(  * No ads - I'm not the product) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(8.3 Two Doors) show newline
(-------------) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(                        CYBERSPACE) show newline
(                            |) show newline
(               +------------+------------+) show newline
(               |                         |) show newline
(         +-----v-----+             +-----v-----+) show newline
(         | Terminal  |             | Friendly  |) show newline
(         |   \(cs\)    |             |   Door    |) show newline
(         +-----+-----+             +-----+-----+) show newline
(               |                         |) show newline
(           Operators                  Novices) show newline
(            Hackers                   Family) show newline
(            Admins                   Everyone) show newline
() show newline
(The terminal offers full power and complexity for those who want it. The) show newline
(friendly door offers drag-and-drop simplicity - same operations,) show newline
(different presentation.) show newline
() show newline
(Both doors lead to the same vault. Both use the same Scheme underneath.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(8.4 Principles) show newline
(--------------) show newline
() show newline
(  * Never dumb down the core - Scheme stays Scheme) show newline
(  * Add layers, don't subtract - Friendly is additional, not replacement) show newline
(  * Same operations - Both doors do the same things) show newline
(  * Gradual revelation - Novices can discover the terminal if curious) show newline
(  * Family friendly - Grandma can use it) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(8.5 The Test) show newline
(------------) show newline
() show newline
(If a novice can create a vault in 30 seconds, add a photo in 5 seconds,) show newline
(invite family in 1 minute, and understand what they have - we've) show newline
(succeeded.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(8.6 The Koan) show newline
(------------) show newline
() show newline
(There is no point scaling to 2^128 if you assume everyone is a Schemer.) show newline
() show newline
(The cryptographic address space, the capability chains, the Merkle) show newline
(proofs — all of that is implementation. The user doesn't sign) show newline
(certificates, they approve a peer. They don't query the vault, they) show newline
(inspect soup.) show newline
() show newline
(If the system requires understanding SPKI to use safely, the system) show newline
(failed. The security properties must emerge from natural actions, not) show newline
(careful ones.) show newline
() show newline
(The complexity serves the simplicity, not the other way around.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
(9. CRYPTOGRAPHIC SELECTIONS) show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(Every cryptographic algorithm in Cyberspace was chosen for specific) show newline
(properties. This section documents the selections and their rationale.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(9.1 Signatures) show newline
(--------------) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(  Algorithm  Use                       Selection Rationale                                               ) show newline
(  Ed25519    Primary signatures        Small keys \(32B\), fast, constant-time, no RNG needed for signing  ) show newline
(  SPHINCS+   Post-quantum \(planned\)    Hash-based, conservative security, stateless                      ) show newline
(  Dilithium  Post-quantum \(planned\)    Lattice-based, smaller signatures than SPHINCS+, NIST selected    ) show newline
(  Lamport    Reference implementation  Educational, hash-only security, foundation for SPHINCS+          ) show newline
() show newline
(Ed25519 is the current standard. Post-quantum migration uses hybrid) show newline
(signatures \(Ed25519 + SPHINCS+ or Dilithium\) to preserve security if) show newline
(either scheme breaks.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(9.2 Hash Functions) show newline
(------------------) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(  Algorithm  Use                            Selection Rationale                                   ) show newline
(  SHA-512    Object identity, signatures    Conservative choice, 256-bit quantum security         ) show newline
(  BLAKE2b    Content addressing, KDF        Faster than SHA-2, proven design, libsodium native    ) show newline
(  SHAKE256   Post-quantum Merkle \(planned\)  XOF for variable output, SHA-3 family, NIST standard  ) show newline
(  Argon2id   Passphrase stretching          Memory-hard, resists GPU/ASIC, winner of PHC          ) show newline
() show newline
(Hash functions survive quantum computers. Shor's algorithm \(exponential) show newline
(speedup\) breaks signatures and key exchange but not hashes. Grover's) show newline
(algorithm provides only quadratic speedup against hashes — halving) show newline
(effective security bits, not destroying them.) show newline
() show newline
(SHA-512's 512 bits become 256-bit quantum security. Still beyond brute) show newline
(force. SHA-256 would drop to 128-bit quantum security — acceptable but) show newline
(less margin. We chose SHA-512 for the conservative 256-bit post-quantum) show newline
(level.) show newline
() show newline
(BLAKE2b \(256-bit output\) provides 128-bit quantum security, sufficient) show newline
(for content addressing where collision resistance matters more than) show newline
(preimage resistance.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(9.3 Symmetric Encryption) show newline
(------------------------) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(  Algorithm           Use                Selection Rationale                       ) show newline
(  XSalsa20-Poly1305   Vault encryption   NaCl default, 24-byte nonce, proven AEAD  ) show newline
(  ChaCha20-Poly1305   Object encryption  IETF standard, 12-byte nonce, streaming   ) show newline
(  XChaCha20-Poly1305  Keystore           Extended nonce \(24B\), random nonce safe   ) show newline
() show newline
(The Salsa20/ChaCha20 family was chosen over AES: no timing attacks, no) show newline
(hardware requirements, Poly1305 is provably secure MAC. The 'X' variants) show newline
(use extended nonces, safe for random generation.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(9.4 Key Exchange) show newline
(----------------) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(  Algorithm  Use                     Selection Rationale                               ) show newline
(  X25519     Ephemeral key exchange  Curve25519 ECDH, constant-time, small keys        ) show newline
(  HKDF       Key derivation          RFC 5869, extract-then-expand, domain separation  ) show newline
() show newline
(X25519 provides forward secrecy for CIP channels. Session keys are) show newline
(derived via HKDF with protocol-specific info strings for domain) show newline
(separation.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(9.5 Secret Sharing) show newline
(------------------) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(  Algorithm   Use                             Selection Rationale                                 ) show newline
(  Shamir SSS  Key backup, threshold recovery  Information-theoretic security, GF\(2^8\) arithmetic  ) show newline
() show newline
(Shamir's scheme splits secrets into n shares where any k can) show newline
(reconstruct. Used for master key backup \(5-of-9\) and threshold) show newline
(governance.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(9.6 Blind Signatures \(Chaum\)) show newline
(----------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(David Chaum's 1982 blind signature scheme enables anonymous credentials.) show newline
(The Library holds four Chaum papers:) show newline
() show newline
(  * Blind Signatures for Untraceable Payments \(1982\) — the foundation) show newline
(  * Untraceable Electronic Cash \(1988, with Fiat & Naor\)) show newline
(  * Untraceable Electronic Mail \(1981\) — mix networks) show newline
(  * The Dining Cryptographers Problem \(1988\) — unconditional anonymity) show newline
() show newline
(Cyberspace uses Chaum-style blind signatures for bearer capabilities:) show newline
(prove authorization without revealing identity. The issuer signs a) show newline
(blinded credential; when unblinded and presented, the signature verifies) show newline
(but cannot be linked to issuance.) show newline
() show newline
(This preserves the choice Bitcoin abandoned: registered capabilities) show newline
(when you need accountability, bearer capabilities when you need privacy.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(9.7 Merkle Trees) show newline
(----------------) show newline
() show newline
(Content authentication via binary hash trees. Current implementation) show newline
(uses SHA-512; post-quantum migration to SHAKE256 or BLAKE3.) show newline
() show newline
(Properties: O\(log n\) inclusion proofs, streaming verification,) show newline
(append-only audit logs. Merkle's 1987 paper is in the Library.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(9.8 Random Number Generation) show newline
(----------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(All randomness flows through libsodium's randombytes_buf\(\), which uses:) show newline
() show newline
(  * Linux: getrandom\(2\) syscall) show newline
(  * macOS: arc4random_buf\(\)) show newline
(  * OpenBSD: arc4random_buf\(\) \(ChaCha20-based\)) show newline
() show newline
(Hardware entropy \(RDRAND/RDSEED\) feeds the OS pool. Quantum RNG \(ID) show newline
(Quantique, drand beacons\) planned for Phase 3+.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(9.9 The TCB Principle) show newline
(---------------------) show newline
() show newline
(The Trusted Computing Base holds only:) show newline
() show newline
(  * Ed25519 sign/verify) show newline
(  * SHA-512 hash) show newline
(  * Certificate chain verification) show newline
() show newline
(Everything else is policy. The TCB is ~1000 lines of OCaml calling) show newline
(libsodium, proven in Coq, frozen. This minimizes the attack surface:) show newline
(prove the crypto, evolve the rest freely.) show newline
() show newline
